Vancouver Crime in Relation to Wealth

STAT 201 202 - Emily Wang, Faraz Hosseinian-Tehrani, Giuliana Kim, Yiran Xiong

Introduction

In recent years, the picturesque city of Vancouver has been grappling with a mounting concern of crime, with a notable surge in theft cases, which has become an increasingly prevalent issue that poses challenges to the safety and security of its residents. CTV news reported on October 27th of this year that 258 arrests were made in a 2-week period as the Vancouver police department continued the shoplifting crackdown[1]. On October 30th, the B.C. Coalition called for immediate government action on theft, vandalism, and violent crime, and its members say they have reached "epidemic proportions'' across the province[2].

Given the prevalent issue, in our project, we will answer the question: How do proportions of theft among all crimes differ between neighbourhoods in Vancouver?. We will be using the crime data set[3] from 2003 to 2023 released by the VPD, to investigate the proportions of robbery, theft of motor vehicles, theft from automotives, and theft under $5,000. The two neighbourhoods we will be comparing are Strathcona (often referred to as Downtown Eastside), the poorest neighbourhood in Vancouver, according to Wikipedia[4] and CBC[5], and Kerrisdale, which is one of the richest neighbourhoods in Vancouver[6][7]. Our location parameter of interest will be the difference of proportions between the two neighbourhoods, and our scale parameter of interest will be the standard deviation. We believe that these two parameters will help us answer our question at hand - comparing the proportions of theft in the two neighbourhoods.

An article published by CBC stated that there were higher incidences of violent crime in poor Vancouver neighbourhoods, and higher incidences of theft in wealthier Vancouver neighbourhoods[8]. Based on this report, we would expect the proportion of theft in Strathcona to be different than the proportion of theft in Kerrisdale.

Hypotheses

Null Hypothesis: The proportion of thefts relative to all crimes is equal between Strathcona and Kerrisdale.

Alternate Hypothesis: The proportion of thefts relative to all crimes is not equal between Strathcona and Kerrisdale.

$$ H_0: p_1 - p_2 = 0 \\ H_a: p_1 - p_2 \neq 0 $$

Methods

Our report conducts a data analysis of crime data from two Vancouver communities, Kerrisdale and Strathcona, with a focus on the proportion of theft-related crimes in these areas. From our process, we first perform a hypothesis test to determine whether the proportions of theft to other crimes are statistically different between Kerrisdale and Strathcona. We will either reject or fail to reject the null hypothesis, which is that the proportion of thefts relative to all crimes is equal between Strathcona and Kerrisdale, by calculating the p-value and comparing it to a significance value of 5%. We will then calculate a 95% confidence interval for the true difference in proportion between the two neighbourhoods. The hypothesis test and confidence intervals will be obtained through both asymptotic and bootstrapping methods.

Several factors strengthen our report and make it reputable. Firstly, our crime data comes directly from the Vancouver Police Department. Using official data lends credibility to the analysis. Secondly, our report analyses the data by summarizing and creating informative plots to visualize the distribution of crime types over the years in Kerrisdale and Strathcona. The tidy data format and analysis make the data easier to understand and work with.

Reading Data

The first step is to read in our data set from the web using the 'read_csv' function. The datasets were originally downloaded from https://geodash.vpd.ca/opendata, where the data for Kerrisdale and Strathcona were in seperate csvs. So, we read the two csvs seperately and then merged them together into a single data frame using rbind. Our raw dataset also contained a lot of unnecessary columns like the exact time (MONTH, DAY, HOUR, MINUTE) and the precise location (HUNDRED_BLOCK, X, Y) of the crime committed, so we selected only the relevant columns to our study such as TYPE, YEAR, and NEIGHBOURHOOD.

In[2]:

Given these two plots, it is clear that Strathcona sees a greater total number of crimes. However, it is difficult to judge which neighbourhood has a higher proportion of thefts. Thus, to calculate the proportion of thefts, we group the data into thefts and non-thefts. Our new column, 'Theft' includes the following theft-related crimes: "Theft of Bicycle", "Theft of Vehicle", "Theft from Vehicle", and "Other Theft". Non-theft related crimes are under the column 'Other', which includes crimes such as "Break and Enter Commercial", "Homicide", among others. We can then calculate the total number of theft related crimes and non-theft related crimes.

Results

Bootstrapping Method

First, we will use bootstrapping to conduct a hypothesis test using the null distribution. We will then obtain a confidence interval using both the percentile and standard error method.

Hypothesis Testing using Bootstrapping

We can test $H_0$ by first assuming it to be true and constructing the null distribution. We will then compute the observed test statistic, which is the observed difference in proportion of theft between Kerrisdale and Strathcona.

In[12]:
# First, combine the two data frames by row so we can do data analysis using the infer package
crimes_grouped <- rbind(kerrisdale_crimes_grouped, strathcona_crimes_grouped)

# Calculate the null distribution
null_distribution <- crimes_grouped |>
    specify(formula = TYPE ~ NEIGHBOURHOOD, success = "Theft") |>
    hypothesize(null = "independence") |>
    generate(reps = 100, type = "permute") |>
    calculate(stat = "diff in props", order = c("Kerrisdale", "Strathcona"))

# Find the observed test statistic
obs_diff_prop <- crimes_grouped |>
    specify(TYPE ~ NEIGHBOURHOOD, success = "Theft") |>
    calculate(stat = "diff in props", order = c("Kerrisdale", "Strathcona"))

print("Observed test statistic:")
obs_diff_prop

[1] "Observed test statistic:"
A infer: 1 1
stat
<dbl>
0.001902851

Now, we can visualize the null distribution with our p-value represented as the red shaded region. The solid dark red line is our observed test statistic.

In[13]:
visualize(null_distribution) +
    shade_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff_prop, direction = "both") +
    labs(x = "Difference in Proportion", caption = "Figure 5: Simulation-Based Null Distribution") +
    theme(plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

Judging by the shaded region in Figure 5, we can see that 0.0019, which is the observed difference of proportion is quite common under our null hypothesis. In other words, since the shaded region is large, our p-value will be large, which means we may end up failing to reject our null hypothesis. Let's verify this by obtaining the exact value of our p-value.

In[14]:
null_distribution |>
    get_p_value(obs_stat = obs_diff_prop, direction = "both")
A tibble: 1 1
p_value
<dbl>
0.66

Since the p-value 0.66 is greater than the significance level $ = 0.05$, we fail to reject $H_0$. We do not have enough evidence to prove a statiscially significant difference in proportion of crime between Kerrisdale and Strathcona.

Because we fail to reject $H_0$, we are at risk of making a Type II error, which would be failing to conclude that the difference in proportions is significant when it in fact is.

Confidence Intervals using Bootstrap Distribution

Now, let's obtain a 95% confidence interval for the difference in proportion. To do so, we will need to use the bootstrap distribution.

In[15]:
bootstrap_distribution <- crimes_grouped |>
    specify(formula = TYPE ~ NEIGHBOURHOOD, success = "Theft") |>
    generate(reps = 100, type = "bootstrap") |>
    calculate(stat = "diff in props", order = c("Kerrisdale", "Strathcona"))

Let's first compute a confidence interval using the percentile method.

In[16]:
percentile_ci <- bootstrap_distribution |>
    get_confidence_interval(level = 0.95, type = "percentile")

percentile_ci
A tibble: 1 2
lower_ciupper_ci
<dbl><dbl>
-0.007458650.01107421

The shorthand interpretation for the 95% confidence interval would be as follows: we are 95% confident that the true difference in population proportions of Kerrisdale and Strathcona is between (-0.0074, 0.0111).

Notice how 0 is included in this confidence interval - this means that we cannot confidently state whether either proportion is larger, as both negative and positive differences in proportions were acquired during our 100 bootstrap samples.

Now, let's visualize the bootstrap distribution with the percentile-based confidence interval shaded in.

In[17]:
visualize(bootstrap_distribution) + 
    shade_confidence_interval(endpoints = percentile_ci) +
    labs(x = "Difference in Proportion", caption = "Figure 6: Percentile-based 95% confidence interval") +
    theme(plot.caption = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

From Figure 6, we can observe that our bootstrap distribution appears to be roughly normally shaped. Hence, we can also use the standard error method to obtain the 95% confidence interval. To do this, we must also include the observed difference in proportion as the center of the confidence interval.

In[18]:
se_ci <- bootstrap_distribution |>
    get_confidence_interval(level = 0.95, type = "se", point_estimate = obs_diff_prop)

The shorthand interpretation for the 95% confidence interval would be as follows: we are 95% confident that the true difference in population proportions of Kerrisdale and Strathcona is between (-0.0083, 0.0121). Compared to the percentile-based confidence interval, the standard error-based one is slightly wider.

Notice how 0 is included in this confidence interval - this means that we cannot confidently state whether either proportion is larger, as the interval spans both positive and negative values.

We can then revisualize the bootstrap distribution with the standard error-based 95% confidence interval.

Asymptotic Method

We will now conduct a hypothesis test and obtain the confidence interval using an asymptotic method with the intention to compare both bootstrapping and asymptotic methods. Asymptotics requires quite a few assumptions to construct the null distribution and is an approximation to the simulation-based method of bootstrapping. By comparing the results of the two methods, we will see if the assumptions for asymptotics hold true for our dataset.

Hypothesis Testing using Asymptotics

The assumptions for a hypothesis test for the difference of two population proportions is as follows:

  • The size of sample must be large enough
  • The sample must be taken in independent fashion
  • The sample is random

To test $H_0$, we use the following test statistic, $Z$:

$$ Z = \frac{\hat{p}_1 - \hat{p}_2}{\sqrt{\hat{p}(1-\hat{p})\left(\frac{1}{n_1} + \frac{1}{n_2}\right)}} $$ where $\hat{p}_1$ and $\hat{p}_2$ are the sample proportions in Kerrisdale and Strathcona, respectively; $n$ is the sample size; and $\hat{p}$ is the pooled proportion, given by:

$$\hat{p} = \frac{n_1\hat{p}_1+n_2\hat{p}_2}{n_1+n_2}$$

Since the population distribution is clearly not Normal since the random variable is a 0-1 variable, we need to rely on the Central Limit Theorem (CLT). The CLT states that given that the sample size is large enough, the null model of $Z$ is approximately $N(0, 1)$.

First, we will calculate the test statistic.

In[20]:
# Calculate sample size for Kerrisdale and Strathcona 
n1 <- sum(crimes_grouped$NEIGHBOURHOOD == "Kerrisdale")
n2 <- sum(crimes_grouped$NEIGHBOURHOOD == "Strathcona")

# Calculate sample proportions in Kerrisdale and Strathcona
phat1 <- crimes_grouped |> filter(NEIGHBOURHOOD == "Kerrisdale", TYPE == "Theft") |>
                                        summarize(phat = n()/n1) |> pull()
phat2 <- crimes_grouped |> filter(NEIGHBOURHOOD == "Strathcona", TYPE == "Theft") |>
                                        summarize(phat = n()/n2) |> pull()

# Calculate pooled proportion
p <- (n1*phat1+n2*phat2)/(n1 + n2)

# Finally, calculate test statistic
test_stat <- (phat1-phat2)/sqrt(p*(1-p)*(1/n1+1/n2))

print("Test statistic:")
test_stat

[1] "Test statistic:"
0.373591430756071

Now, we will calculate the p-value using pnorm.

In[21]:
p_val <- 2 * pnorm(test_stat, lower.tail = FALSE)

print("p-value:")
p_val

Since the p-value 0.71 is greater than the significance level $ = 0.05$, we fail to reject $H_0$. We do not have enough evidence to prove a statiscially significant difference in proportion of crime between Kerrisdale and Strathcona.

Recall that the p-value for our bootstrapping method was 0.66 and compare that with our p-value of 0.71 using asymptotics. The p-values have a difference of 5% with asymptotics' p-value being higher than bootstrapping's p-value. Despite this difference, both p-values lead to the same conclusion - a failure to reject the null hypothesis. Thus, it seems that the assumptions are reasonable to make and asymptotics is a suitable method for this hypothesis test.

This suggests that regardless of the method used (bootstrapping or asymptotics), the evidence from the data does not provide sufficient support to refute the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis. In other words, there isn't enough statistical significance to claim a difference in theft proportions based on the observed data.

Confidence Intervals using Asymptotics

Now, let's obtain a 95% confidence interval for the difference in proportion. To do so using asymptotics, we will use the following formulas:

$$CI({p}_1 - {p}_2) = (\hat{p}_1 - \hat{p}_2) \pm z^* \sqrt{\frac{\hat{p}_1(1-\hat{p}_1)}{n_1}+\frac{\hat{p}_2(1-\hat{p}_2)}{n_2}}$$

In[23]:
# Obtain the critical value
crit_value <- qnorm(1-0.05/2)

# Calculate the confidence interval using the formula
crime_ci <- tibble(
     lower_ci = (phat1 - phat2) - crit_value * sqrt(phat1*(1-phat1)/n1 + phat2*(1-phat2)/n2),
     upper_ci = (phat1 - phat2) + crit_value * sqrt(phat1*(1-phat1)/n1 + phat2*(1-phat2)/n2)
 )

crime_ci
A tibble: 1 2
lower_ciupper_ci
<dbl><dbl>
-0.008077780.01188348

The shorthand interpretation for the 95% confidence interval would be as follows: we are 95% confident that the true difference in population proportions of Kerrisdale and Strathcona is between (-0.0081, 0.0119).

Notice how 0 is included in this confidence interval - this means that we cannot confidently state whether either proportion is larger, as the interval spans both positive and negative values.

Now, we can compare the asymptotic confidence interval with the two bootstrapping ones.

In[24]:
# Combine all 3 confidence intervals into one tibble to compare
combined_ci <- bind_rows(
  percentile_ci %>% mutate(type = "percentile"),

We observe that the asymptotic confidence interval has the widest range, followed by standard error-based and percentile-based has the smallest range. However, the difference in range is minimal and the confidence intervals are all extremely similar. They also all include the value 0.

Discussion

In our analysis, we used both bootstrapping and asymptotic methods to test our hypotheses. These two methods obtained similar results, which strengthens the reliability of our findings. While bootstrapping is computationally intensive, it makes fewer assumptions and is a powerful method especially when the sample size is moderate or when the underlying distribution is unknown. Asymptotic methods, on the other hand, are based on theoretical distributions and are less computationally demanding. Given the large sample size and the nature of our data, both methods were appropriate. However, bootstrapping may be preferred for its fewer assumptions and greater flexibility. It is also particularly useful for educational purposes, as it allows us to visualize the sampling distribution and understand the concept of variability in estimates.

As shown in the results section, we found no significant statistical difference in the proportion of theft between Strathcona and Kerrisdale. The p-values that have been obtained have been fairly large, at 0.71 using the asymptotic method, and 0.66 using the bootstrap method. In both methods, we did not have enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that there is no significant difference between the proportions of theft in Strathcona and Kerrisdale. The 95% confidence intervals of the difference in proportions constructed using both the bootstrapping method and the asymptotic method included 0, which further supports the null hypothesis of there being no significant difference between the two neighbourhoods theft proportions.

The results we obtained were not the results we were expecting to find, as we were expecting to find that the proportion of theft in Kerrisdale would be higher than that of Strathcona. The reason we have obtained results different from what we were expecting may be because in the study the CBC article[8] was citing, the researchers Andresen and Tarah Hodgkinson tracked 10 types of crime across 22 neighbourhoods in Vancouver. Even though we used the same data set for our analyses, Andresen and Hodgkinson used a larger dataset, which may have contributed to obtaining different results. Andresen and Hodgkinsons study also used census data from Statistics Canada, to find out how socio-economic factors may have played a role in the increase in crime.

As shown in preliminary results, specifically in Figures 1 and 2, Strathcona has a significantly higher number of crimes than Kerrisdale, despite their population sizes being close. Future studies or research could certainly be done on different aspects of this topic to help us understand why more crimes occur in some neighbourhoods than others. Some future research questions may be to investigate if there is a difference in proportions of specific types of theft(theft from vehicles, robbery, theft under $5,000, etc), to investigate different neighbourhoods other than Strathcona and Kerrisdale, or to investigate whether there are different crime rates depending on the time of the day, day of the week, or even depending on the time of the year.
